    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (75.95) and **Junior Caminero** (74.54) headlining the lineup as our most efficient starts. **Pete Crow-Armstrong** benefits significantly from a favorable matchup against Tobias Myers, where a combination of a 12% boost in SP skill and a strong 14% platoon advantage elevates him to the top of our board. Similarly, **Junior Caminero** finds himself in an ideal position against Mitch Keller; the combination of a favorable wind direction blowing out (+5%) and a top-of-the-order boost (+8%) makes him a high-floor, high-ceiling play. While **Carson Benge** (67.24) and **Trea Turner** (70.45) are also elite considerations, both face Grant Holmes in a matchup where their leadoff status allows them to maximize plate appearances, effectively offsetting the risks inherent in an aggressive 5x5 Roto build.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision today involved the marginal gap between **Jerar Encarnacion** (54.11) and **Victor Scott II** (46.01). While the optimizer favored **Jerar Encarnacion** due to his power potential in a matchup against Miles Mikolas, **Victor Scott II** was the closest consideration for the bench. Ultimately, the decision to leave **Victor Scott II** on the bench was driven by the significant penalty associated with his assumed #9 spot in the lineup (-8%), which severely limits his R and RBI potential despite the team's ongoing prioritization of SB. We are also monitoring a 34% rain risk in the games involving **Carson Benge** and **Pete Crow-Armstrong**; should those matchups be delayed or postponed, we will be forced to rotate in bench assets like **Colt Keith** or **Luke Raley** to ensure we maintain our daily efficiency targets. \n\nFinally, managers should note that while **Dillon Dingler** (48.46) faces a formidable arm in Garrett Crochet, his score remains viable due to a massive 14% boost from dynamic platoon splits. We are also navigating a high number of \"